INFLUENZA PANDEMIC (H1N1) 2009 (13): COMMENTS
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

In this update:
[1] comment on disease severity
[2] comment on obesity risk

******
[1] Comment on disease severity
Date: Tue 21 Jul 2009
From: Julian Tang <jwtang49@hotmail.com>


At the risk of recent over-exposure, I would just like to follow up
on Dr Peter Sandman's comments in the ProMED post: "Influenza
pandemic (H1N1) 2009 (06): case reporting, archive number
20090717.2553." The comments by Peter Sandman are timely; finally,
someone has stated explicitly what many of us who are involved
diagnostically in this field really suspect. Yet this may go against
the popular notion in many countries that this influenza pandemic
(H1N1) 2009 virus is a more deadly virus than seasonal influenza.

However, there is an issue about the number of severe cases being
admitted to ICUs [Intensive Care Units]; these are being cited as
being higher for this influenza pandemic (H1N1) 2009 virus than for
seasonal influenza. This may also be a problem of case ascertainment
bias for the seasonal influenza cases.

Usually for seasonal influenza (for which very few cases are lab-
confirmed), since it is familiar, most people may not attend
healthcare services so readily. So the patients who finally present
with severe respiratory failure to ICUs are often diagnosed with
bacterial pneumonias that may in fact be secondary to an initial
respiratory virus infection. Yet, at the time of presentation, this
virus may no longer be detectable, and ICUs usually do not look for
them.

Having spoken to various ICU teams over the years, they agree that
they rarely screen for respiratory virus infections in their ICU
patients for 2 main reasons: 1) even if there is a respiratory virus
(e.g. adenovirus, parainfluenza virus, influenza virus, etc.), there
is not much they can do about it; even oseltamivir's beneficial
effects are fairly marginal, and it needs to be given within 48 hours
of infection for such benefits to be seen, treating the presenting
secondary bacterial infection with respiratory support generally
works quite well, so why waste further resources on screening for any
earlier virus infection?

However, such undiagnosed cases of influenza that eventually lead to
secondary bacterial pneumonias may give a false impression of a lower
mortality for seasonal influenza infections as compared to the
current influenza pandemic H1N1 2009 strain. This may simply be
because in this pandemic climate with the influenza pandemic (H1N1)
2009 virus rapidly becoming more prevalent in the community, patients
are more aware of viral infections generally, so they present earlier
to healthcare services whilst the virus is still present and
detectable.

Thus, their entire illness (which may, therefore, entail a longer
admission for observation, whether the infection eventually turns out
to be mild, moderate severe, or fatal) and any resulting
case-fatality can be attributed to this new virus.

This may thus give a misleading impression that this new pandemic
strain is causing more severe infections with a higher mortality in
hospitalized patients than seasonal influenza, which may, in fact,
not be the case, though demonstrating this may be practically
difficult (it would require people who would normally stay at home to
tough out their illness to come into hospital for a diagnostic
nasopharyngeal swab to be taken).

--
