[2] Comment on obesity risk
Date: Wed 22 Jul 2009
From: Tom Kiedrzynski <TomK@spc.int>


As we're working in the Pacific Island region, where there is a high
prevalence of obesity in some of the populations, it is important for
us to know the real risk that obesity plays for influenza pandemic
(H1N1) 2009 virus infection complications, as many countries have
scarce resources to respond to the pandemic, especially for patient
care. Until now, I haven't seen an estimate of the risk obesity (and
possibly other potential risk factors, e.g. pregnancy) poses with the
current pandemic virus.

As mentioned by the moderator, "...obesity may be a risk factor for
severe complications following infections with this virus," and
nothing has been proven yet. This is also what is explained in the
MMWR article referred to hereunder: "Intensive-Care Patients With
Severe Novel Influenza A (H1N1) Virus Infection --- Michigan, June
2009."

Similarly, the title of the ProMED posting below should include a
question mark at the end, as some "fast readers" may interpret it as
a fact that obesity is a risk factor.

Clearly, if we have a certain prevalence of obesity in the
population, it is expected that complications happen in the same
proportion of this group as for healthy adults, and, with reference
to the MMWR article, the USA is known for a high prevalence of
obesity. So the question to answer is: are complications
significantly more frequent among the obese population than among
healthy adults once they are infected by the influenza pandemic
(H1N1) 2009 virus? How could we get this answer?

Another question to answer would be whether healthy adults are a
group at risk themselves, and of what age group exactly, as the
pandemic seems to affect more young adults.

"Erring on the cautious side of the line" is logical, but sometimes
it seems to become nearly as strong as scientifically proven facts.

In the Pacific Island region as elsewhere, especially in developing
countries, we'd like to see more evidence in order to be able to
allocate our meager resources more appropriately and give special
attention to populations at real risk for complications, if this is
possible.

And for sure, we welcome any hint regarding this type of evidence, as
there may be information that we have missed!

--
